'''Ika Odori''' (いか踊り) is a dance from {{ill|Hakodate|ja|函館市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, inspired by the city’s signature product: squid.
== Overview == The dance was created in 1981 by the “Ika Odori Executive Committee,” a volunteer group of Hakodate citizens, for the {{ill|Hakodate Port Festival|ja|函館港まつり|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>函館市史通説編4 p677 - p691</ref> Unlike the {{ill|Hakodate Port Dance|ja|函館港おどり|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or {{ill|Isn't it good? ~Hakodate Port Song~|ja|いいんでないかい〜函館港唄〜|qq=draft}}, the concept of Ika Odori was designed to be simple so anyone could participate. Toshiyuki Masuno, an employee at a fishery company, choreographed the dance,<ref name="212club">マルミ屋宮下食品課長代理増野敏幸 函館 - 212CLUB 創刊2号（弐壱弐研究所 1988th year 7月）102頁</ref> which debuted with a group of 20 dancers.
The dance gained recognition through its recording in 1986 and through the 1990s {{ill|Ikanopolis Plan|ja|イカノポリス計画|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a community development initiative that designated squid as Hakodate’s official fish.<ref>函館港まつりで「いか踊り」を踊ろう! 函館観光公式ガイドはこぶら 函館市 2024th year 2月10日閲覧</ref>
Ika Odori is a prominent feature in Hakodate Port Festival events, such as the “Wasshoi Hakodate” parade (formerly the “10,000-person parade” and later the “30,000-person parade”).<ref>"開港164周年記念函館港まつりワッショイはこだて開催要綱" 函館港まつり実行委員会 2023rd year </ref> It is also performed by open participation groups.<ref>"開港164周年記念函館港まつり 「ワッショイはこだて」いか踊りの部 自由参加の参加方法について" 函館港まつり実行委員会 2023rd year </ref> Additionally, the dance is often presented by members of the Hakodate Cruise Promotion Association to send off cruise ships at Hakodate’s port.<ref>[https://wwwtb.mlit.go.jp/hokkaido/bunyabetsu/kaiun/cruise/cruise3_hakodate2.html "函館地区クルーズ振興協議会の活動"] 国土交通省 2024th year 2月10日閲覧</ref> {{Main|Hakodate Port Festival#Content}}
== Cultural Exchange == As part of the “Seikan Twin City Exchange” between Hakodate and {{ill|Aomori|ja|青森市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, reciprocal performances of {{ill|Nebuta|ja|ねぶた|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and Ika Odori are held in alternating years. In 2006, Ika Odori was featured at the opening of the Nebuta daytime parade on August 7, while in 2007, Aomori’s Nebuta float traveled to Hakodate for an exchange.
